# URL Routing & Structure (Nuxt, CMS-Ready)

Single source of truth for URL patterns on mid-scale airport hotel sites (Nuxt + structured CMS). Aligns with adapters at the boundary—no vendor field names in UI.

## 1. Overview

**Purpose:** Predictable URLs that scale, rank clearly, and map 1:1 to CMS collections and Nuxt file routes.

**Principles:** simplicity (short paths), scalability (lists + `[slug]` detail), SEO clarity (stable kebab slugs), CMS compatibility (slug-driven fetches in loaders/composables—not in leaf components).

## 2. Route Classification

### Static routes

**What qualifies:** Fixed editorial pages with a **fixed schema** (not a CMS “builder” page). URLs do not include `[slug]`; content may still come from CMS as single records or static local data.

**Why not dynamic:** One URL per page forever; no per-entity slug in the path.

**Examples:** Home, Meetings & Events, Dining, Amenities, Privacy Policy, Contact, Hotel Policies.

### Dynamic routes

**What qualifies:** Repeated entities (many rooms, posts, offers) addressed by **`[slug]`** in a stable parent segment.

**CMS control:** Collections expose `slug` (+ title, body, SEO, etc.). App resolves `route.params.slug` in page/route middleware, fetches by slug via adapter, normalizes to app models.

#### Rooms

- Listing: all rooms (`/rooms`).
- Detail: one room (`/rooms/[slug]`).

#### Blog

- Listing: archive/index (`/blog`).
- Article: one post (`/blog/[slug]`).

#### Offers

- Listing: all offers (`/offers`).
- Detail: one offer, including direct-booking benefits in **data**, same URL pattern (`/offers/[slug]`).

